# Intuition of this Problem:
1) *[1,3,5,6], target = 0, for this type of example in which target is less than arr[0], in this case the index of "last" is always "-1".*

2) *[1,3,5,6], target = 7, for this type of example in which target is greater than arr[n-1], in this case the index of "last" is always "n-1".*

3) *"last" is always point to the index which is just smaller or equal to the target at the end of the program.
Ex - [1,3,5,6], target = 2, for this case "last" is pointing to 0th index which is just smaller than target i.e. 2.*

*It means no need to cover "edge case" additionally. When you will return "last + 1" at the end of code then it will automatically cover both the cases i.e. 1st and 2nd.*
