solutions.content:
The tricky part is "if(start>end) return -(start+1);" if this if statement is true, we are sure that target is NOT FOUND, so we just need to return the insertion position.

Now let's think about cases which makes start > end.
The previous caller must be the case start==end, so mid==start==end then 

 - case 1: binarySearchInsert(nums, mid+1, end, target), meaning
   nums[mid]<target, the insertion position should be mid+1 (insert
   target after mid) 
 - case 2: binarySearchInsert(nums, start, mid-1,    target), meaing
   nums[mid]>target, the insertion position should be    mid (insert
   target into mid and shift old mid value afterwards)

So it is clear, in the next call, when start>end, the start should be the insertion position. 

 - But WAIT, if target is found, the found idx>=0, if target if NOT
   FOUND, the insertion idx also >=0, then how to differentiate it is
   found or not? Here we use a trick to return negative value when not
   found.
 - But WAIT again, how about the found value is ZERO? -0==0, so we use
   another trick to increment insertion idx before negation.

This is just what the Java's Collections binarySearch API returns. It all makes sense.

    public class Solution {

        public int binarySearchInsert(int[] nums, int start, int end, int target) {
            if(start>end)
                return -(start+1); 
            int mid = start+(end-start)/2;
            if(nums[mid]==target)
                return mid;
            else if(nums[mid]<target)
                return binarySearchInsert(nums, mid+1, end, target);
            else
                return binarySearchInsert(nums, start, mid-1, target);
        }

        public int searchInsert(int[] nums, int target) {
            int idx = binarySearchInsert(nums, 0, nums.length-1, target);
            return idx>=0 ? idx : -idx-1;
        }
    }

